#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:5
msgid "Selectors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:7
msgid ""
"When you're scraping web pages, the most common task you need to perform is "
"to extract data from the HTML source. There are several libraries available "
"to achieve this, such as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:11
msgid ""
"`BeautifulSoup`_ is a very popular web scraping library among Python "
"programmers which constructs a Python object based on the structure of the "
"HTML code and also deals with bad markup reasonably well, but it has one "
"drawback: it's slow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:16
msgid ""
"`lxml`_ is an XML parsing library (which also parses HTML) with a pythonic "
"API based on :mod:`~xml.etree.ElementTree`. (lxml is not part of the Python "
"standard library.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:20
msgid ""
"Scrapy comes with its own mechanism for extracting data. They're called "
"selectors because they \"select\" certain parts of the HTML document "
"specified either by `XPath`_ or `CSS`_ expressions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:24
msgid ""
"`XPath`_ is a language for selecting nodes in XML documents, which can also "
"be used with HTML. `CSS`_ is a language for applying styles to HTML "
"documents. It defines selectors to associate those styles with specific HTML "
"elements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:29
msgid ""
"Scrapy Selectors is a thin wrapper around `parsel`_ library; the purpose of "
"this wrapper is to provide better integration with Scrapy Response objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:32
msgid ""
"`parsel`_ is a stand-alone web scraping library which can be used without "
"Scrapy. It uses `lxml`_ library under the hood, and implements an easy API "
"on top of lxml API. It means Scrapy selectors are very similar in speed and "
"parsing accuracy to lxml."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:44 ../../../topics/selectors.rst:108
msgid "Using selectors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:47
msgid "Constructing selectors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:53
msgid ""
"Response objects expose a :class:`~scrapy.Selector` instance on ``."
"selector`` attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:56
msgid ""
">>> response.selector.xpath(\"//span/text()\").get()\n"
"'good'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:61
msgid ""
"Querying responses using XPath and CSS is so common that responses include "
"two more shortcuts: ``response.xpath()`` and ``response.css()``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:64
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath(\"//span/text()\").get()\n"
"'good'\n"
">>> response.css(\"span::text\").get()\n"
"'good'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:73
msgid ""
"Scrapy selectors are instances of :class:`~scrapy.Selector` class "
"constructed by passing either :class:`~scrapy.http.TextResponse` object or "
"markup as a string (in ``text`` argument)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:77
msgid ""
"Usually there is no need to construct Scrapy selectors manually: "
"``response`` object is available in Spider callbacks, so in most cases it is "
"more convenient to use ``response.css()`` and ``response.xpath()`` "
"shortcuts. By using ``response.selector`` or one of these shortcuts you can "
"also ensure the response body is parsed only once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:83
msgid ""
"But if required, it is possible to use ``Selector`` directly. Constructing "
"from text:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:86
msgid ""
">>> from scrapy.selector import Selector\n"
">>> body = \"<html><body><span>good</span></body></html>\"\n"
">>> Selector(text=body).xpath(\"//span/text()\").get()\n"
"'good'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:93
msgid ""
"Constructing from response - :class:`~scrapy.http.HtmlResponse` is one of :"
"class:`~scrapy.http.TextResponse` subclasses:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:96
msgid ""
">>> from scrapy.selector import Selector\n"
">>> from scrapy.http import HtmlResponse\n"
">>> response = HtmlResponse(url=\"http://example.com\", body=body, "
"encoding=\"utf-8\")\n"
">>> Selector(response=response).xpath(\"//span/text()\").get()\n"
"'good'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:104
msgid ""
"``Selector`` automatically chooses the best parsing rules (XML vs HTML) "
"based on input type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:117
msgid ""
"To explain how to use the selectors we'll use the ``Scrapy shell`` (which "
"provides interactive testing) and an example page located in the Scrapy "
"documentation server:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:121
msgid "https://docs.scrapy.org/en/latest/_static/selectors-sample1.html"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:125
msgid "For the sake of completeness, here's its full HTML code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:127
msgid ""
"<!DOCTYPE html>\n"
"\n"
"<html>\n"
"  <head>\n"
"    <base href='http://example.com/' />\n"
"    <title>Example website</title>\n"
"  </head>\n"
"  <body>\n"
"    <div id='images'>\n"
"      <a href='image1.html'>Name: My image 1 <br /><img src='image1_thumb."
"jpg' alt='image1'/></a>\n"
"      <a href='image2.html'>Name: My image 2 <br /><img src='image2_thumb."
"jpg' alt='image2'/></a>\n"
"      <a href='image3.html'>Name: My image 3 <br /><img src='image3_thumb."
"jpg' alt='image3'/></a>\n"
"      <a href='image4.html'>Name: My image 4 <br /><img src='image4_thumb."
"jpg' alt='image4'/></a>\n"
"      <a href='image5.html'>Name: My image 5 <br /><img src='image5_thumb."
"jpg' alt='image5'/></a>\n"
"    </div>\n"
"  </body>\n"
"</html>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:132
msgid "First, let's open the shell::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:134
msgid ""
"scrapy shell https://docs.scrapy.org/en/latest/_static/selectors-sample1.html"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:136
msgid ""
"Then, after the shell loads, you'll have the response available as "
"``response`` shell variable, and its attached selector in ``response."
"selector`` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:139
msgid ""
"Since we're dealing with HTML, the selector will automatically use an HTML "
"parser."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:143
msgid ""
"So, by looking at the :ref:`HTML code <topics-selectors-htmlcode>` of that "
"page, let's construct an XPath for selecting the text inside the title tag:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:146
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath(\"//title/text()\")\n"
"[<Selector query='//title/text()' data='Example website'>]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:151
msgid ""
"To actually extract the textual data, you must call the selector ``.get()`` "
"or ``.getall()`` methods, as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:154
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath(\"//title/text()\").getall()\n"
"['Example website']\n"
">>> response.xpath(\"//title/text()\").get()\n"
"'Example website'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:161
msgid ""
"``.get()`` always returns a single result; if there are several matches, "
"content of a first match is returned; if there are no matches, None is "
"returned. ``.getall()`` returns a list with all results."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:165
msgid ""
"Notice that CSS selectors can select text or attribute nodes using CSS3 "
"pseudo-elements:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:168 ../../../topics/selectors.rst:304
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"title::text\").get()\n"
"'Example website'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:173
msgid ""
"As you can see, ``.xpath()`` and ``.css()`` methods return a :class:`~scrapy."
"selector.SelectorList` instance, which is a list of new selectors. This API "
"can be used for quickly selecting nested data:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:177
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"img\").xpath(\"@src\").getall()\n"
"['image1_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image2_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image3_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image4_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image5_thumb.jpg']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:186
msgid ""
"If you want to extract only the first matched element, you can call the "
"selector ``.get()`` (or its alias ``.extract_first()`` commonly used in "
"previous Scrapy versions):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:190
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath('//div[@id=\"images\"]/a/text()').get()\n"
"'Name: My image 1 '"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:195
msgid "It returns ``None`` if no element was found:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:197
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath('//div[@id=\"not-exists\"]/text()').get() is None\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:202
msgid ""
"A default return value can be provided as an argument, to be used instead of "
"``None``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:205
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath('//div[@id=\"not-exists\"]/text()').get(default=\"not-"
"found\")\n"
"'not-found'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:210
msgid ""
"Instead of using e.g. ``'@src'`` XPath it is possible to query for "
"attributes using ``.attrib`` property of a :class:`~scrapy.Selector`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:213
msgid ""
">>> [img.attrib[\"src\"] for img in response.css(\"img\")]\n"
"['image1_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image2_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image3_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image4_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image5_thumb.jpg']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:222
msgid ""
"As a shortcut, ``.attrib`` is also available on SelectorList directly; it "
"returns attributes for the first matching element:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:225
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"img\").attrib[\"src\"]\n"
"'image1_thumb.jpg'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:230
msgid ""
"This is most useful when only a single result is expected, e.g. when "
"selecting by id, or selecting unique elements on a web page:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:233
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"base\").attrib[\"href\"]\n"
"'http://example.com/'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:238
msgid "Now we're going to get the base URL and some image links:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:240
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath(\"//base/@href\").get()\n"
"'http://example.com/'\n"
"\n"
">>> response.css(\"base::attr(href)\").get()\n"
"'http://example.com/'\n"
"\n"
">>> response.css(\"base\").attrib[\"href\"]\n"
"'http://example.com/'\n"
"\n"
">>> response.xpath('//a[contains(@href, \"image\")]/@href').getall()\n"
"['image1.html',\n"
"'image2.html',\n"
"'image3.html',\n"
"'image4.html',\n"
"'image5.html']\n"
"\n"
">>> response.css(\"a[href*=image]::attr(href)\").getall()\n"
"['image1.html',\n"
"'image2.html',\n"
"'image3.html',\n"
"'image4.html',\n"
"'image5.html']\n"
"\n"
">>> response.xpath('//a[contains(@href, \"image\")]/img/@src').getall()\n"
"['image1_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image2_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image3_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image4_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image5_thumb.jpg']\n"
"\n"
">>> response.css(\"a[href*=image] img::attr(src)\").getall()\n"
"['image1_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image2_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image3_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image4_thumb.jpg',\n"
"'image5_thumb.jpg']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:282
msgid "Extensions to CSS Selectors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:284
msgid ""
"Per W3C standards, `CSS selectors`_ do not support selecting text nodes or "
"attribute values. But selecting these is so essential in a web scraping "
"context that Scrapy (parsel) implements a couple of **non-standard pseudo-"
"elements**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:289
msgid "to select text nodes, use ``::text``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:290
msgid ""
"to select attribute values, use ``::attr(name)`` where *name* is the name of "
"the attribute that you want the value of"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:294
msgid ""
"These pseudo-elements are Scrapy-/Parsel-specific. They will most probably "
"not work with other libraries like `lxml`_ or `PyQuery`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:300
msgid "Examples:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:302
msgid ""
"``title::text`` selects children text nodes of a descendant ``<title>`` "
"element:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:309
msgid ""
"``*::text`` selects all descendant text nodes of the current selector "
"context:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:311
msgid "..skip: next .. code-block:: pycon"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:327
msgid ""
"``foo::text`` returns no results if ``foo`` element exists, but contains no "
"text (i.e. text is empty):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:330
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"img::text\").getall()\n"
"[]\n"
"\n"
"This means ``.css('foo::text').get()`` could return None even if an element\n"
"exists. Use ``default=''`` if you always want a string:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:338
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"img::text\").get()\n"
">>> response.css(\"img::text\").get(default=\"\")\n"
"''"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:344
msgid ""
"``a::attr(href)`` selects the *href* attribute value of descendant links:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:346
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"a::attr(href)\").getall()\n"
"['image1.html',\n"
"'image2.html',\n"
"'image3.html',\n"
"'image4.html',\n"
"'image5.html']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:356 ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1076
#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1118
msgid "See also: :ref:`selecting-attributes`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:359
msgid ""
"You cannot chain these pseudo-elements. But in practice it would not make "
"much sense: text nodes do not have attributes, and attribute values are "
"string values already and do not have children nodes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:368
msgid "Nesting selectors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:370
msgid ""
"The selection methods (``.xpath()`` or ``.css()``) return a list of "
"selectors of the same type, so you can call the selection methods for those "
"selectors too. Here's an example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:374
msgid ""
">>> links = response.xpath('//a[contains(@href, \"image\")]')\n"
">>> links.getall()\n"
"['<a href=\"image1.html\">Name: My image 1 <br><img src=\"image1_thumb.jpg\" "
"alt=\"image1\"></a>',\n"
"'<a href=\"image2.html\">Name: My image 2 <br><img src=\"image2_thumb.jpg\" "
"alt=\"image2\"></a>',\n"
"'<a href=\"image3.html\">Name: My image 3 <br><img src=\"image3_thumb.jpg\" "
"alt=\"image3\"></a>',\n"
"'<a href=\"image4.html\">Name: My image 4 <br><img src=\"image4_thumb.jpg\" "
"alt=\"image4\"></a>',\n"
"'<a href=\"image5.html\">Name: My image 5 <br><img src=\"image5_thumb.jpg\" "
"alt=\"image5\"></a>']\n"
"\n"
">>> for index, link in enumerate(links):\n"
"...     href_xpath = link.xpath(\"@href\").get()\n"
"...     img_xpath = link.xpath(\"img/@src\").get()\n"
"...     print(f\"Link number {index} points to url {href_xpath!r} and image "
"{img_xpath!r}\")\n"
"...\n"
"Link number 0 points to url 'image1.html' and image 'image1_thumb.jpg'\n"
"Link number 1 points to url 'image2.html' and image 'image2_thumb.jpg'\n"
"Link number 2 points to url 'image3.html' and image 'image3_thumb.jpg'\n"
"Link number 3 points to url 'image4.html' and image 'image4_thumb.jpg'\n"
"Link number 4 points to url 'image5.html' and image 'image5_thumb.jpg'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:398
msgid "Selecting element attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:400
msgid ""
"There are several ways to get a value of an attribute. First, one can use "
"XPath syntax:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:403
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath(\"//a/@href\").getall()\n"
"['image1.html', 'image2.html', 'image3.html', 'image4.html', 'image5.html']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:408
msgid ""
"XPath syntax has a few advantages: it is a standard XPath feature, and "
"``@attributes`` can be used in other parts of an XPath expression - e.g. it "
"is possible to filter by attribute value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:412
msgid ""
"Scrapy also provides an extension to CSS selectors (``::attr(...)``) which "
"allows to get attribute values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:415
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"a::attr(href)\").getall()\n"
"['image1.html', 'image2.html', 'image3.html', 'image4.html', 'image5.html']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:420
msgid ""
"In addition to that, there is a ``.attrib`` property of Selector. You can "
"use it if you prefer to lookup attributes in Python code, without using "
"XPaths or CSS extensions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:424
msgid ""
">>> [a.attrib[\"href\"] for a in response.css(\"a\")]\n"
"['image1.html', 'image2.html', 'image3.html', 'image4.html', 'image5.html']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:429
msgid ""
"This property is also available on SelectorList; it returns a dictionary "
"with attributes of a first matching element. It is convenient to use when a "
"selector is expected to give a single result (e.g. when selecting by element "
"ID, or when selecting an unique element on a page):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:434
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"base\").attrib\n"
"{'href': 'http://example.com/'}\n"
">>> response.css(\"base\").attrib[\"href\"]\n"
"'http://example.com/'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:441
msgid "``.attrib`` property of an empty SelectorList is empty:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:443
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"foo\").attrib\n"
"{}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:449
msgid "Using selectors with regular expressions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:451
msgid ""
":class:`~scrapy.Selector` also has a ``.re()`` method for extracting data "
"using regular expressions. However, unlike using ``.xpath()`` or ``.css()`` "
"methods, ``.re()`` returns a list of strings. So you can't construct nested "
"``.re()`` calls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:456
msgid ""
"Here's an example used to extract image names from the :ref:`HTML code "
"<topics-selectors-htmlcode>` above:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:459
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath('//a[contains(@href, \"image\")]/text()').re(r\"Name:"
"\\s*(.*)\")\n"
"['My image 1 ',\n"
"'My image 2 ',\n"
"'My image 3 ',\n"
"'My image 4 ',\n"
"'My image 5 ']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:468
msgid ""
"There's an additional helper reciprocating ``.get()`` (and its alias ``."
"extract_first()``) for ``.re()``, named ``.re_first()``. Use it to extract "
"just the first matching string:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:472
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath('//a[contains(@href, \"image\")]/text()')."
"re_first(r\"Name:\\s*(.*)\")\n"
"'My image 1 '"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:480
msgid "extract() and extract_first()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:482
msgid ""
"If you're a long-time Scrapy user, you're probably familiar with ``."
"extract()`` and ``.extract_first()`` selector methods. Many blog posts and "
"tutorials are using them as well. These methods are still supported by "
"Scrapy, there are **no plans** to deprecate them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:487
msgid ""
"However, Scrapy usage docs are now written using ``.get()`` and ``."
"getall()`` methods. We feel that these new methods result in a more concise "
"and readable code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:491
msgid "The following examples show how these methods map to each other."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:493
msgid "``SelectorList.get()`` is the same as ``SelectorList.extract_first()``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:495
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"a::attr(href)\").get()\n"
"'image1.html'\n"
">>> response.css(\"a::attr(href)\").extract_first()\n"
"'image1.html'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:502
msgid "``SelectorList.getall()`` is the same as ``SelectorList.extract()``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:504
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"a::attr(href)\").getall()\n"
"['image1.html', 'image2.html', 'image3.html', 'image4.html', 'image5.html']\n"
">>> response.css(\"a::attr(href)\").extract()\n"
"['image1.html', 'image2.html', 'image3.html', 'image4.html', 'image5.html']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:511
msgid "``Selector.get()`` is the same as ``Selector.extract()``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:513
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"a::attr(href)\")[0].get()\n"
"'image1.html'\n"
">>> response.css(\"a::attr(href)\")[0].extract()\n"
"'image1.html'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:520
msgid ""
"For consistency, there is also ``Selector.getall()``, which returns a list:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:522
msgid ""
">>> response.css(\"a::attr(href)\")[0].getall()\n"
"['image1.html']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:527
msgid ""
"So, the main difference is that output of ``.get()`` and ``.getall()`` "
"methods is more predictable: ``.get()`` always returns a single result, ``."
"getall()`` always returns a list of all extracted results. With ``."
"extract()`` method it was not always obvious if a result is a list or not; "
"to get a single result either ``.extract()`` or ``.extract_first()`` should "
"be called."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:537
msgid "Working with XPaths"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:539
msgid ""
"Here are some tips which may help you to use XPath with Scrapy selectors "
"effectively. If you are not much familiar with XPath yet, you may want to "
"take a look first at this `XPath tutorial`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:544
msgid "Some of the tips are based on `this post from Zyte's blog`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:553
msgid "Working with relative XPaths"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:555
msgid ""
"Keep in mind that if you are nesting selectors and use an XPath that starts "
"with ``/``, that XPath will be absolute to the document and not relative to "
"the ``Selector`` you're calling it from."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:559
msgid ""
"For example, suppose you want to extract all ``<p>`` elements inside "
"``<div>`` elements. First, you would get all ``<div>`` elements:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:562
msgid ">>> divs = response.xpath(\"//div\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:566
msgid ""
"At first, you may be tempted to use the following approach, which is wrong, "
"as it actually extracts all ``<p>`` elements from the document, not only "
"those inside ``<div>`` elements:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:570
msgid ""
">>> for p in divs.xpath(\"//p\"):  # this is wrong - gets all <p> from the "
"whole document\n"
"...     print(p.get())\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:576
msgid ""
"This is the proper way to do it (note the dot prefixing the ``.//p`` XPath):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:578
msgid ""
">>> for p in divs.xpath(\".//p\"):  # extracts all <p> inside\n"
"...     print(p.get())\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:584
msgid "Another common case would be to extract all direct ``<p>`` children:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:586
msgid ""
">>> for p in divs.xpath(\"p\"):\n"
"...     print(p.get())\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:592
msgid ""
"For more details about relative XPaths see the `Location Paths`_ section in "
"the XPath specification."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:598
msgid "When querying by class, consider using CSS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:600
msgid ""
"Because an element can contain multiple CSS classes, the XPath way to select "
"elements by class is the rather verbose::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:603
msgid "*[contains(concat(' ', normalize-space(@class), ' '), ' someclass ')]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:605
msgid ""
"If you use ``@class='someclass'`` you may end up missing elements that have "
"other classes, and if you just use ``contains(@class, 'someclass')`` to make "
"up for that you may end up with more elements that you want, if they have a "
"different class name that shares the string ``someclass``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:610
msgid ""
"As it turns out, Scrapy selectors allow you to chain selectors, so most of "
"the time you can just select by class using CSS and then switch to XPath "
"when needed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:613
msgid ""
">>> from scrapy import Selector\n"
">>> sel = Selector(\n"
"...     text='<div class=\"hero shout\"><time datetime=\"2014-07-23 "
"19:00\">Special date</time></div>'\n"
"... )\n"
">>> sel.css(\".shout\").xpath(\"./time/@datetime\").getall()\n"
"['2014-07-23 19:00']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:622
msgid ""
"This is cleaner than using the verbose XPath trick shown above. Just "
"remember to use the ``.`` in the XPath expressions that will follow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:626
msgid "Beware of the difference between //node[1] and (//node)[1]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:628
msgid ""
"``//node[1]`` selects all the nodes occurring first under their respective "
"parents."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:630
msgid ""
"``(//node)[1]`` selects all the nodes in the document, and then gets only "
"the first of them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:632 ../../../topics/selectors.rst:690
msgid "Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:634
msgid ""
">>> from scrapy import Selector\n"
">>> sel = Selector(\n"
"...     text=\"\"\"\n"
"...     <ul class=\"list\">\n"
"...         <li>1</li>\n"
"...         <li>2</li>\n"
"...         <li>3</li>\n"
"...     </ul>\n"
"...     <ul class=\"list\">\n"
"...         <li>4</li>\n"
"...         <li>5</li>\n"
"...         <li>6</li>\n"
"...     </ul>\"\"\"\n"
"... )\n"
">>> xp = lambda x: sel.xpath(x).getall()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:652
msgid "This gets all first ``<li>``  elements under whatever it is its parent:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:654
msgid ""
">>> xp(\"//li[1]\")\n"
"['<li>1</li>', '<li>4</li>']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:659
msgid "And this gets the first ``<li>``  element in the whole document:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:661
msgid ""
">>> xp(\"(//li)[1]\")\n"
"['<li>1</li>']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:666
msgid "This gets all first ``<li>``  elements under an ``<ul>``  parent:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:668
msgid ""
">>> xp(\"//ul/li[1]\")\n"
"['<li>1</li>', '<li>4</li>']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:673
msgid ""
"And this gets the first ``<li>``  element under an ``<ul>``  parent in the "
"whole document:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:675
msgid ""
">>> xp(\"(//ul/li)[1]\")\n"
"['<li>1</li>']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:681
msgid "Using text nodes in a condition"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:683
msgid ""
"When you need to use the text content as argument to an `XPath string "
"function`_, avoid using ``.//text()`` and use just ``.`` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:686
msgid ""
"This is because the expression ``.//text()`` yields a collection of text "
"elements -- a *node-set*. And when a node-set is converted to a string, "
"which happens when it is passed as argument to a string function like "
"``contains()`` or ``starts-with()``, it results in the text for the first "
"element only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:692
msgid ""
">>> from scrapy import Selector\n"
">>> sel = Selector(\n"
"...     text='<a href=\"#\">Click here to go to the <strong>Next Page</"
"strong></a>'\n"
"... )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:699
msgid "Converting a *node-set* to string:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:701
msgid ""
">>> sel.xpath(\"//a//text()\").getall()  # take a peek at the node-set\n"
"['Click here to go to the ', 'Next Page']\n"
">>> sel.xpath(\"string(//a[1]//text())\").getall()  # convert it to string\n"
"['Click here to go to the ']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:708
msgid ""
"A *node* converted to a string, however, puts together the text of itself "
"plus of all its descendants:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:710
msgid ""
">>> sel.xpath(\"//a[1]\").getall()  # select the first node\n"
"['<a href=\"#\">Click here to go to the <strong>Next Page</strong></a>']\n"
">>> sel.xpath(\"string(//a[1])\").getall()  # convert it to string\n"
"['Click here to go to the Next Page']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:717
msgid ""
"So, using the ``.//text()`` node-set won't select anything in this case:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:719
msgid ""
">>> sel.xpath(\"//a[contains(.//text(), 'Next Page')]\").getall()\n"
"[]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:724
msgid "But using the ``.`` to mean the node, works:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:726
msgid ""
">>> sel.xpath(\"//a[contains(., 'Next Page')]\").getall()\n"
"['<a href=\"#\">Click here to go to the <strong>Next Page</strong></a>']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:736
msgid "Variables in XPath expressions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:738
msgid ""
"XPath allows you to reference variables in your XPath expressions, using the "
"``$somevariable`` syntax. This is somewhat similar to parameterized queries "
"or prepared statements in the SQL world where you replace some arguments in "
"your queries with placeholders like ``?``, which are then substituted with "
"values passed with the query."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:744
msgid ""
"Here's an example to match an element based on its \"id\" attribute value, "
"without hard-coding it (that was shown previously):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:747
msgid ""
">>> # `$val` used in the expression, a `val` argument needs to be passed\n"
">>> response.xpath(\"//div[@id=$val]/a/text()\", val=\"images\").get()\n"
"'Name: My image 1 '"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:753
msgid ""
"Here's another example, to find the \"id\" attribute of a ``<div>`` tag "
"containing five ``<a>`` children (here we pass the value ``5`` as an "
"integer):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:756
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath(\"//div[count(a)=$cnt]/@id\", cnt=5).get()\n"
"'images'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:761
msgid ""
"All variable references must have a binding value when calling ``.xpath()`` "
"(otherwise you'll get a ``ValueError: XPath error:`` exception). This is "
"done by passing as many named arguments as necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:765
msgid ""
"`parsel`_, the library powering Scrapy selectors, has more details and "
"examples on `XPath variables`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:774
msgid "Removing namespaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:778
msgid ""
"When dealing with scraping projects, it is often quite convenient to get rid "
"of namespaces altogether and just work with element names, to write more "
"simple/convenient XPaths. You can use the :meth:`.Selector."
"remove_namespaces` method for that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:783
msgid ""
"Let's show an example that illustrates this with the Python Insider blog "
"atom feed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:787
msgid "First, we open the shell with the url we want to scrape::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:789
msgid "$ scrapy shell https://feeds.feedburner.com/PythonInsider"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:791
msgid "This is how the file starts::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:793
msgid ""
"<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n"
"<?xml-stylesheet ...\n"
"<feed xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\"\n"
"      xmlns:openSearch=\"http://a9.com/-/spec/opensearchrss/1.0/\"\n"
"      xmlns:blogger=\"http://schemas.google.com/blogger/2008\"\n"
"      xmlns:georss=\"http://www.georss.org/georss\"\n"
"      xmlns:gd=\"http://schemas.google.com/g/2005\"\n"
"      xmlns:thr=\"http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0\"\n"
"      xmlns:feedburner=\"http://rssnamespace.org/feedburner/ext/1.0\">\n"
"  ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:804
msgid ""
"You can see several namespace declarations including a default ``\"http://"
"www.w3.org/2005/Atom\"`` and another one using the ``gd:`` prefix for "
"``\"http://schemas.google.com/g/2005\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:810
msgid ""
"Once in the shell we can try selecting all ``<link>`` objects and see that "
"it doesn't work (because the Atom XML namespace is obfuscating those nodes):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:813
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath(\"//link\")\n"
"[]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:818
msgid ""
"But once we call the :meth:`.Selector.remove_namespaces` method, all nodes "
"can be accessed directly by their names:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:821
msgid ""
">>> response.selector.remove_namespaces()\n"
">>> response.xpath(\"//link\")\n"
"[<Selector query='//link' data='<link rel=\"alternate\" type=\"text/html\" "
"h'>,\n"
"    <Selector query='//link' data='<link rel=\"next\" type=\"application/"
"atom+'>,\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:829
msgid ""
"If you wonder why the namespace removal procedure isn't always called by "
"default instead of having to call it manually, this is because of two "
"reasons, which, in order of relevance, are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:833
msgid ""
"Removing namespaces requires to iterate and modify all nodes in the "
"document, which is a reasonably expensive operation to perform by default "
"for all documents crawled by Scrapy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:837
msgid ""
"There could be some cases where using namespaces is actually required, in "
"case some element names clash between namespaces. These cases are very rare "
"though."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:844
msgid "Using EXSLT extensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:846
msgid ""
"Being built atop `lxml`_, Scrapy selectors support some `EXSLT`_ extensions "
"and come with these pre-registered namespaces to use in XPath expressions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:851
msgid "prefix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:851
msgid "namespace"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:851
msgid "usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:853
msgid "re"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:853
msgid "\\http://exslt.org/regular-expressions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:853
msgid "`regular expressions`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:854
msgid "set"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:854
msgid "\\http://exslt.org/sets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:854
msgid "`set manipulation`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:858
msgid "Regular expressions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:860
msgid ""
"The ``test()`` function, for example, can prove quite useful when XPath's "
"``starts-with()`` or ``contains()`` are not sufficient."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:863
msgid ""
"Example selecting links in list item with a \"class\" attribute ending with "
"a digit:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:865
msgid ""
">>> from scrapy import Selector\n"
">>> doc = \"\"\"\n"
"... <div>\n"
"...     <ul>\n"
"...         <li class=\"item-0\"><a href=\"link1.html\">first item</a></li>\n"
"...         <li class=\"item-1\"><a href=\"link2.html\">second item</a></"
"li>\n"
"...         <li class=\"item-inactive\"><a href=\"link3.html\">third item</"
"a></li>\n"
"...         <li class=\"item-1\"><a href=\"link4.html\">fourth item</a></"
"li>\n"
"...         <li class=\"item-0\"><a href=\"link5.html\">fifth item</a></li>\n"
"...     </ul>\n"
"... </div>\n"
"... \"\"\"\n"
">>> sel = Selector(text=doc, type=\"html\")\n"
">>> sel.xpath(\"//li//@href\").getall()\n"
"['link1.html', 'link2.html', 'link3.html', 'link4.html', 'link5.html']\n"
">>> sel.xpath(r'//li[re:test(@class, \"item-\\d$\")]//@href').getall()\n"
"['link1.html', 'link2.html', 'link4.html', 'link5.html']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:885
msgid ""
"C library ``libxslt`` doesn't natively support EXSLT regular expressions so "
"`lxml`_'s implementation uses hooks to Python's ``re`` module. Thus, using "
"regexp functions in your XPath expressions may add a small performance "
"penalty."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:891
msgid "Set operations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:893
msgid ""
"These can be handy for excluding parts of a document tree before extracting "
"text elements for example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:896
msgid ""
"Example extracting microdata (sample content taken from https://schema.org/"
"Product) with groups of itemscopes and corresponding itemprops:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:901
msgid ""
">>> doc = \"\"\"\n"
"... <div itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Product\">\n"
"...   <span itemprop=\"name\">Kenmore White 17\" Microwave</span>\n"
"...   <img src=\"kenmore-microwave-17in.jpg\" alt='Kenmore 17\" Microwave' /"
">\n"
"...   <div itemprop=\"aggregateRating\"\n"
"...     itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/AggregateRating\">\n"
"...    Rated <span itemprop=\"ratingValue\">3.5</span>/5\n"
"...    based on <span itemprop=\"reviewCount\">11</span> customer reviews\n"
"...   </div>\n"
"...   <div itemprop=\"offers\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/"
"Offer\">\n"
"...     <span itemprop=\"price\">$55.00</span>\n"
"...     <link itemprop=\"availability\" href=\"http://schema.org/InStock\" /"
">In stock\n"
"...   </div>\n"
"...   Product description:\n"
"...   <span itemprop=\"description\">0.7 cubic feet countertop microwave.\n"
"...   Has six preset cooking categories and convenience features like\n"
"...   Add-A-Minute and Child Lock.</span>\n"
"...   Customer reviews:\n"
"...   <div itemprop=\"review\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/"
"Review\">\n"
"...     <span itemprop=\"name\">Not a happy camper</span> -\n"
"...     by <span itemprop=\"author\">Ellie</span>,\n"
"...     <meta itemprop=\"datePublished\" content=\"2011-04-01\">April 1, "
"2011\n"
"...     <div itemprop=\"reviewRating\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema."
"org/Rating\">\n"
"...       <meta itemprop=\"worstRating\" content = \"1\">\n"
"...       <span itemprop=\"ratingValue\">1</span>/\n"
"...       <span itemprop=\"bestRating\">5</span>stars\n"
"...     </div>\n"
"...     <span itemprop=\"description\">The lamp burned out and now I have to "
"replace\n"
"...     it. </span>\n"
"...   </div>\n"
"...   <div itemprop=\"review\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/"
"Review\">\n"
"...     <span itemprop=\"name\">Value purchase</span> -\n"
"...     by <span itemprop=\"author\">Lucas</span>,\n"
"...     <meta itemprop=\"datePublished\" content=\"2011-03-25\">March 25, "
"2011\n"
"...     <div itemprop=\"reviewRating\" itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema."
"org/Rating\">\n"
"...       <meta itemprop=\"worstRating\" content = \"1\"/>\n"
"...       <span itemprop=\"ratingValue\">4</span>/\n"
"...       <span itemprop=\"bestRating\">5</span>stars\n"
"...     </div>\n"
"...     <span itemprop=\"description\">Great microwave for the price. It is "
"small and\n"
"...     fits in my apartment.</span>\n"
"...   </div>\n"
"...   ...\n"
"... </div>\n"
"... \"\"\"\n"
">>> sel = Selector(text=doc, type=\"html\")\n"
">>> for scope in sel.xpath(\"//div[@itemscope]\"):\n"
"...     print(\"current scope:\", scope.xpath(\"@itemtype\").getall())\n"
"...     props = scope.xpath(\n"
"...         \"\"\"\n"
"...                 set:difference(./descendant::*/@itemprop,\n"
"...                                .//*[@itemscope]/*/@itemprop)\"\"\"\n"
"...     )\n"
"...     print(f\"    properties: {props.getall()}\")\n"
"...     print(\"\")\n"
"...\n"
"\n"
"current scope: ['http://schema.org/Product']\n"
"    properties: ['name', 'aggregateRating', 'offers', 'description', "
"'review', 'review']\n"
"\n"
"current scope: ['http://schema.org/AggregateRating']\n"
"    properties: ['ratingValue', 'reviewCount']\n"
"\n"
"current scope: ['http://schema.org/Offer']\n"
"    properties: ['price', 'availability']\n"
"\n"
"current scope: ['http://schema.org/Review']\n"
"    properties: ['name', 'author', 'datePublished', 'reviewRating', "
"'description']\n"
"\n"
"current scope: ['http://schema.org/Rating']\n"
"    properties: ['worstRating', 'ratingValue', 'bestRating']\n"
"\n"
"current scope: ['http://schema.org/Review']\n"
"    properties: ['name', 'author', 'datePublished', 'reviewRating', "
"'description']\n"
"\n"
"current scope: ['http://schema.org/Rating']\n"
"    properties: ['worstRating', 'ratingValue', 'bestRating']"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:982
msgid ""
"Here we first iterate over ``itemscope`` elements, and for each one, we look "
"for all ``itemprops`` elements and exclude those that are themselves inside "
"another ``itemscope``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:991
msgid "Other XPath extensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:993
msgid ""
"Scrapy selectors also provide a sorely missed XPath extension function ``has-"
"class`` that returns ``True`` for nodes that have all of the specified HTML "
"classes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:997
msgid "For the following HTML:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:999
msgid ""
">>> from scrapy.http import HtmlResponse\n"
">>> response = HtmlResponse(\n"
"...     url=\"http://example.com\",\n"
"...     body=\"\"\"\n"
"... <html>\n"
"...     <body>\n"
"...         <p class=\"foo bar-baz\">First</p>\n"
"...         <p class=\"foo\">Second</p>\n"
"...         <p class=\"bar\">Third</p>\n"
"...         <p>Fourth</p>\n"
"...     </body>\n"
"... </html>\n"
"... \"\"\",\n"
"...     encoding=\"utf-8\",\n"
"... )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1017
msgid "You can use it like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1019
msgid ""
">>> response.xpath('//p[has-class(\"foo\")]')\n"
"[<Selector query='//p[has-class(\"foo\")]' data='<p class=\"foo bar-"
"baz\">First</p>'>,\n"
"<Selector query='//p[has-class(\"foo\")]' data='<p class=\"foo\">Second</"
"p>'>]\n"
">>> response.xpath('//p[has-class(\"foo\", \"bar-baz\")]')\n"
"[<Selector query='//p[has-class(\"foo\", \"bar-baz\")]' data='<p class=\"foo "
"bar-baz\">First</p>'>]\n"
">>> response.xpath('//p[has-class(\"foo\", \"bar\")]')\n"
"[]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1029
msgid ""
"So XPath ``//p[has-class(\"foo\", \"bar-baz\")]`` is roughly equivalent to "
"CSS ``p.foo.bar-baz``.  Please note, that it is slower in most of the cases, "
"because it's a pure-Python function that's invoked for every node in "
"question whereas the CSS lookup is translated into XPath and thus runs more "
"efficiently, so performance-wise its uses are limited to situations that are "
"not easily described with CSS selectors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1036
msgid ""
"Parsel also simplifies adding your own XPath extensions with :func:`~parsel."
"xpathfuncs.set_xpathfunc`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1042
msgid "Built-in Selectors reference"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1048
msgid "Selector objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../scrapy/selector/unified.py:docstring of
#: scrapy.selector.unified.Selector:1
msgid ""
"An instance of :class:`Selector` is a wrapper over response to select "
"certain parts of its content."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../scrapy/selector/unified.py:docstring of
#: scrapy.selector.unified.Selector:4
msgid ""
"``response`` is an :class:`~scrapy.http.HtmlResponse` or an :class:`~scrapy."
"http.XmlResponse` object that will be used for selecting and extracting data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../scrapy/selector/unified.py:docstring of
#: scrapy.selector.unified.Selector:8
msgid ""
"``text`` is a unicode string or utf-8 encoded text for cases when a "
"``response`` isn't available. Using ``text`` and ``response`` together is "
"undefined behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../scrapy/selector/unified.py:docstring of
#: scrapy.selector.unified.Selector:12
msgid ""
"``type`` defines the selector type, it can be ``\"html\"``, ``\"xml\"``, "
"``\"json\"`` or ``None`` (default)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../scrapy/selector/unified.py:docstring of
#: scrapy.selector.unified.Selector:15
msgid ""
"If ``type`` is ``None``, the selector automatically chooses the best type "
"based on ``response`` type (see below), or defaults to ``\"html\"`` in case "
"it is used together with ``text``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../scrapy/selector/unified.py:docstring of
#: scrapy.selector.unified.Selector:19
msgid ""
"If ``type`` is ``None`` and a ``response`` is passed, the selector type is "
"inferred from the response type as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../scrapy/selector/unified.py:docstring of
#: scrapy.selector.unified.Selector:22
msgid "``\"html\"`` for :class:`~scrapy.http.HtmlResponse` type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../scrapy/selector/unified.py:docstring of
#: scrapy.selector.unified.Selector:23
msgid "``\"xml\"`` for :class:`~scrapy.http.XmlResponse` type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../scrapy/selector/unified.py:docstring of
#: scrapy.selector.unified.Selector:24
msgid "``\"json\"`` for :class:`~scrapy.http.TextResponse` type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../scrapy/selector/unified.py:docstring of
#: scrapy.selector.unified.Selector:25
msgid "``\"html\"`` for anything else"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../scrapy/selector/unified.py:docstring of
#: scrapy.selector.unified.Selector:27
msgid ""
"Otherwise, if ``type`` is set, the selector type will be forced and no "
"detection will occur."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.xpath:1
msgid ""
"Find nodes matching the xpath ``query`` and return the result as a :class:"
"`SelectorList` instance with all elements flattened. List elements "
"implement :class:`Selector` interface too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.xpath:5
msgid "``query`` is a string containing the XPATH query to apply."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.xpath:7 parsel.selector.SelectorList.xpath:6
msgid ""
"``namespaces`` is an optional ``prefix: namespace-uri`` mapping (dict) for "
"additional prefixes to those registered with ``register_namespace(prefix, "
"uri)``. Contrary to ``register_namespace()``, these prefixes are not saved "
"for future calls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.xpath:12 parsel.selector.SelectorList.xpath:11
msgid ""
"Any additional named arguments can be used to pass values for XPath "
"variables in the XPath expression, e.g.::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.xpath:15 parsel.selector.SelectorList.xpath:14
msgid "selector.xpath('//a[href=$url]', url=\"http://www.example.com\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1056
msgid "For convenience, this method can be called as ``response.xpath()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.css:1
msgid ""
"Apply the given CSS selector and return a :class:`SelectorList` instance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.css:3
msgid "``query`` is a string containing the CSS selector to apply."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.css:5
msgid ""
"In the background, CSS queries are translated into XPath queries using "
"`cssselect`_ library and run ``.xpath()`` method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1062
msgid "For convenience, this method can be called as ``response.css()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.jmespath:1
msgid ""
"Find objects matching the JMESPath ``query`` and return the result as a :"
"class:`SelectorList` instance with all elements flattened. List elements "
"implement :class:`Selector` interface too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.jmespath:5
msgid ""
"``query`` is a string containing the `JMESPath <https://jmespath.org/>`_ "
"query to apply."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.jmespath:8
#: parsel.selector.SelectorList.jmespath:6
msgid ""
"Any additional named arguments are passed to the underlying ``jmespath."
"search`` call, e.g.::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.jmespath:11
#: parsel.selector.SelectorList.jmespath:9
msgid ""
"selector.jmespath('author.name', options=jmespath."
"Options(dict_cls=collections.OrderedDict))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1068
msgid "For convenience, this method can be called as ``response.jmespath()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.get:1
msgid "Serialize and return the matched nodes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.get:3
msgid ""
"For HTML and XML, the result is always a string, and percent-encoded content "
"is unquoted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1072 ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1106
#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1110
msgid "See also: :ref:`old-extraction-api`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docstring of scrapy.Selector.attrib:1
msgid ""
"Return the attributes dictionary for underlying element. For JSON selectors, "
"return an empty dict."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.re:1
msgid "Apply the given regex and return a list of strings with the matches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.re:4
msgid ""
"``regex`` can be either a compiled regular expression or a string which will "
"be compiled to a regular expression using ``re.compile(regex)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.re:7 parsel.selector.Selector.re_first:5
msgid ""
"By default, character entity references are replaced by their corresponding "
"character (except for ``&amp;`` and ``&lt;``). Passing ``replace_entities`` "
"as ``False`` switches off these replacements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.re_first:1
msgid ""
"Apply the given regex and return the first string which matches. If there is "
"no match, return the default value (``None`` if the argument is not "
"provided)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.register_namespace:1
msgid ""
"Register the given namespace to be used in this :class:`Selector`. Without "
"registering namespaces you can't select or extract data from non-standard "
"namespaces. See :ref:`selector-examples-xml`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.remove_namespaces:1
msgid ""
"Remove all namespaces, allowing to traverse the document using namespace-"
"less xpaths. See :ref:`removing-namespaces`. For JSON selectors, this method "
"does nothing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.__bool__:1
msgid ""
"Return ``True`` if there is any real content selected or ``False`` "
"otherwise.  In other words, the boolean value of a :class:`Selector` is "
"given by the contents it selects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.Selector.getall:1
msgid "Serialize and return the matched node in a 1-element list of strings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1090
msgid ""
"This method is added to Selector for consistency; it is more useful with "
"SelectorList. See also: :ref:`old-extraction-api`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1094
msgid "SelectorList objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../scrapy/selector/unified.py:docstring of
#: scrapy.selector.unified.SelectorList:1
msgid ""
"The :class:`SelectorList` class is a subclass of the builtin ``list`` class, "
"which provides a few additional methods."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.SelectorList.xpath:1
msgid ""
"Call the ``.xpath()`` method for each element in this list and return their "
"results flattened as another :class:`SelectorList`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.SelectorList.xpath:4
msgid "``xpath`` is the same argument as the one in :meth:`Selector.xpath`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.SelectorList.css:1
msgid ""
"Call the ``.css()`` method for each element in this list and return their "
"results flattened as another :class:`SelectorList`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.SelectorList.css:4
msgid "``query`` is the same argument as the one in :meth:`Selector.css`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.SelectorList.jmespath:1
msgid ""
"Call the ``.jmespath()`` method for each element in this list and return "
"their results flattened as another :class:`SelectorList`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.SelectorList.jmespath:4
msgid "``query`` is the same argument as the one in :meth:`Selector.jmespath`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.SelectorList.getall:1
msgid ""
"Call the ``.get()`` method for each element is this list and return their "
"results flattened, as a list of strings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.SelectorList.get:1
msgid ""
"Return the result of ``.get()`` for the first element in this list. If the "
"list is empty, return the default value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.SelectorList.re:1
msgid ""
"Call the ``.re()`` method for each element in this list and return their "
"results flattened, as a list of strings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.SelectorList.re:4 parsel.selector.SelectorList.re_first:6
msgid ""
"By default, character entity references are replaced by their corresponding "
"character (except for ``&amp;`` and ``&lt;``. Passing ``replace_entities`` "
"as ``False`` switches off these replacements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.12/site-packages/parsel/selector.py:docstring
#: of parsel.selector.SelectorList.re_first:1
msgid ""
"Call the ``.re()`` method for the first element in this list and return the "
"result in an string. If the list is empty or the regex doesn't match "
"anything, return the default value (``None`` if the argument is not "
"provided)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docstring of scrapy.selector.SelectorList.attrib:1
msgid ""
"Return the attributes dictionary for the first element. If the list is "
"empty, return an empty dict."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1123
msgid "Examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1128
msgid "Selector examples on HTML response"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1130
msgid ""
"Here are some :class:`~scrapy.Selector` examples to illustrate several "
"concepts. In all cases, we assume there is already a :class:`~scrapy."
"Selector` instantiated with a :class:`~scrapy.http.HtmlResponse` object like "
"this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1134
msgid "sel = Selector(html_response)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1138
msgid ""
"Select all ``<h1>`` elements from an HTML response body, returning a list "
"of :class:`~scrapy.Selector` objects (i.e. a :class:`SelectorList` object):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1141
msgid "sel.xpath(\"//h1\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1145
msgid ""
"Extract the text of all ``<h1>`` elements from an HTML response body, "
"returning a list of strings:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1148
msgid ""
"sel.xpath(\"//h1\").getall()  # this includes the h1 tag\n"
"sel.xpath(\"//h1/text()\").getall()  # this excludes the h1 tag"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1153
msgid "Iterate over all ``<p>`` tags and print their class attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1156
msgid ""
"for node in sel.xpath(\"//p\"):\n"
"    print(node.attrib[\"class\"])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1165
msgid "Selector examples on XML response"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1169
msgid ""
"Here are some examples to illustrate concepts for :class:`~scrapy.Selector` "
"objects instantiated with an :class:`~scrapy.http.XmlResponse` object:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1172
msgid "sel = Selector(xml_response)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1176
msgid ""
"Select all ``<product>`` elements from an XML response body, returning a "
"list of :class:`~scrapy.Selector` objects (i.e. a :class:`SelectorList` "
"object):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1179
msgid "sel.xpath(\"//product\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1183
msgid ""
"Extract all prices from a `Google Base XML feed`_ which requires registering "
"a namespace:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/selectors.rst:1186
msgid ""
"sel.register_namespace(\"g\", \"http://base.google.com/ns/1.0\")\n"
"sel.xpath(\"//g:price\").getall()"
msgstr ""
